cards.desc:
We need to design two things (could be one page, or two, or....):

- User input piece
- Output of results

---

From this trello card: https://trello.com/c/0UVj4Gjc/44-problem-statement

---

As a user I am having a particular symptom, and I want to consider what drug (or drugs) might be causing that symptom

Taking multiple drugs and trying to figure out the interactions between those

"Want to visualize the impact of taking multiple drugs and their possible adverse events".

"Which drug is most likely causing an adverse effect."
	
I am a patient/or guardian taking multiple medications and don't which one to start looking at.
cards.name: Review Problem:  As a person interested in the effects of multiple drugs,  I would like to see a visualization of an adverse event associated with a drug regime and be able to play with it to gain an understanding.

cards.desc:
- Draw some lines on your blank paper to create a template like the one attached

- Spend 5 minutes generating low-fi sketches of solutions for the org homepage, keeping in mind the different personas, stories and hypotheses already generated

- These sketches should be visual articulations: UI sketches, workflows, diagrams, etc. Use simple shapes like circles, squares and triangles!
cards.name: Individual Idea generation (8 minutes) (.13)

cards.desc:
- Give each participant 2 minutes to present her/his sketches to the team

- State which persona/audience you were solving a problem for, which hypotheses, explain the sketch

- Team members should provide feedback to the presenter - focus on clarifying the presenter's intentions
cards.name: Presentation / Critique (2 min/person) (.3)
Decide what to move forward with

cards.desc:
If we have time....

- take your original 6 ideas and the feedback you received to refine thinking into a single larger sketch on a single sheet of paper

- goal is to develop a more evolved version of the idea with most merit
cards.name: Iterate and refine (5 minutes) (.083)

cards.desc:
- the team must now converge on one idea, the one they feel has the biggest chance for success

- this idea will serve as the basis for wireframes, coded prototypes, etc.

- if necessary, create a backlog of good ideas that aren't incorporated into the sketch
cards.name: Team idea generation (45 minutes) (.75)
An advanced practice nurse/prescriber specialty family practice and clinical education.  I use this site to determine clearance for medical devices (CLIA waived), product safety, etc.
Justice advocate seeking to demonstrate that most drug testing being done on white males leads to more side effects for women and minority genetic groups.
Advocate of natural healing seeking to emphasize danger of prescribed drugs over natural remedies.
Adult caring for elderly parent(s) and managing their prescriptions.
Enter symptom, and medications taking, to show which medication are known to cause symptom.

Grandparent Guardian: Enter your dependents medicines and review all possible adverse events aggregated for the set of medicines. See this as a function of time vs number of people prescribed those meds. Tie in to other information about those meds. Focus on drug interaction possibilities. This is a side affect management system.
An app that a doctor (or patient) could use prior to prescribing multiple drugs to validate if there are adverse effects with each other.
Citizen science to find potential correlations etc
Build a visual map of all drug events, and be able to replay them across time. Show a blinking map of your city to show the events.
Prescription tool for adults caring for elderly parents
Look up reactions to drugs I am taking
Walled-garden community in which only professionals can play --- we can make our github repo workable for that purpose.  Using Drupal and virtualization should be possible.
User takes a picture with their mobile phone (or enters pill identifying information) to quickly retrieve the adverse effects.
look-ahead type search, where I start typing "hyper..." and it automatically starts showing me medications prescribed for hypertension and hyperactivity.  Gogglize the database.
Use the UNII to find a way to search for gluten-free, vegan, etc. medicines, and look for reactions based on incredients rather than drug.
Create an adverse alert system in which you customize the drugs of interest to you, and receive alerts on conditions.
Find people whose loved ones are taking a similar profile to your meds.
User is presented with common symptoms for their drug(s)
Second level MVP would be adding a symptom field and seeing chart with interactions
Second level: Hover over entered drugs to see a modal with some additional data about that drug?

cards.desc:
###Notes:
- Let's stay as simple as we can
- Great to be able to do comparisons but too broad a use case will be too challenging - we can always further develop a simple idea later if we have time
- Characteristics of the MVP: get connected to data, show data related to adverse affects; Nice to have would be to normalize the data and then look at combinations of drugs
- Is there a sub-MVP that would deliver value? Reverse the order of operations: enter drugs in first, see most common symptoms (see Dan's sketches)
- Could this be a widget that could be embedded into another website?
- Three cases:

1 just list drugs
2 just enter symptom (not as useful)
3 enter drugs and symptoms

- Do we want to have a gender select field?

###Ideas to move forward with:
- Start with Owen's as a base (considering last three years)
- Enter drugs first (multiple drugs)
- Use autocomplete fields
- See a list of suggested common symptoms to choose from (or add ones that are not included in an autocomplete), see :https://trello.com/c/1v3i5BQ9/11-owen
- Treat time as a secondary consideration after MVP is done

The data does not seem to support this kind of mapping.  A drug has a flag of 'patient.drug.drugcharacterization' that has one entry for 3 = Interacting drug   but there is nothing that I see that expressly says or connects drug A interacts with drug B.

Data mining of event aggregation could be done to bubble up some of these possibilities from the data, but they would be weak at best if the data is there.
